Execution Layer
Features
F1: Structured inquiry form  primary digital entry point, replaces calls, saves partial submissions
F2: CRM lead pipeline  tracks all leads across states: new → needs_info → ready → matched → booked → permit_pending → permit_in_review → permit_approved → coordination → closed
F3: Internal dashboard  ops team view of pipeline health, pending actions, booking status, and permit tracking
F4: Client dashboard and profile  self-serve status view, reduces inbound calls
F5: Automated messaging  human-like email and WhatsApp triggered by state changes, reminders, nudges, and inactivity detection
F6: Reusable client profiles  pre-fills known data on re-inquiry, client confirms instead of re-entering
F7: Permit lifecycle tracker  generates checklist, initiates permit process, tracks status through pending → submitted → in_review → approved or rejected
F8: Workflow status tracker  visual pipeline showing stage, owner, last action, next action
F9: Analytics dashboard  conversion rates, volume, drop-off points, time-to-booking
F10: AI location recommendation  semantic search over location inventory with ranked shortlist and reasoning
F11: Partial inquiry capture  saves incomplete submissions as leads in needs_info state
F12: Follow-up system  scheduled outreach to leads missing required fields within 0 to 72 hours
F13: Lead nurturing system  long-interval re-engagement for inactive leads at 7 or more days








AI Services
LLM is used at fixed, bounded points only. It never controls flow. It assists interpretation, ranking, and communication.
A1: IntakeService


Parses raw inquiry text into structured fields
Writes lead record to database
LLM usage: required
A2: ReadinessService


Scores lead completeness
Outputs: ready or needs_info, plus a list of missing fields
LLM usage: required
A3: MatchingService


Embeds client requirements and runs semantic search over location inventory
LLM ranks and explains shortlist
If results are poor: one clarification loop allowed  sends one question to client, reprocesses on response
If still no good match after clarification: C1 moves lead to a fallback state and ops team is notified for manual review
LLM usage: required
A4: PermitService


Infers permit requirements from shoot type, location, and duration
Generates structured checklist stored against booking
Initiates permit process: sets permit status to pending
Tracks permit lifecycle: pending → submitted → in_review → approved or rejected
On rejection: notifies ops team and client via A5, flags for manual resolution
On approval: notifies C1 to advance booking to coordination stage
C1 sends reminders if permit stays in a stage beyond expected time
LLM usage: optional, rules-based fallback available
A5: CommunicationService


Single sending layer for all outgoing messages
Template-first  every state transition maps to a pre-written template
Also triggered by: reminders (time-based), nudges (inactivity-based), and permit status updates
LLM optionally rewrites tone and phrasing only, never changes facts, dates, names, or instructions
If LLM rewrite fails validation, original template is sent
Never invents facts  data always supplied by WorkflowEngine
Neither C4 nor A6 send directly  everything routes through A5
LLM usage: optional (rewrite and tone only)
A6: NurturingService


Long-term re-engagement for leads inactive for 7 or more days
Cadence and timing are deterministic  rule-based schedule (weekly or biweekly), not decided by LLM
LLM used only to personalize message content based on client history
Passes final message to A5 for sending
LLM usage: optional (personalization only)
Core Services
Fully deterministic. No LLM. These own reliability, control, and all state transitions.
C1: WorkflowEngine


Owns and enforces the state machine  no transition happens without it
Actively triggers downstream services on every state change
Handles retries: if a service fails, C1 retries with backoff before escalating
Enforces inactivity rules: detects stale states at needs_info, matched, and permit stages and triggers appropriate action
Sends time-based reminders and nudges via A5 independently of state changes
Single source of truth for all system state
C2: RoutingService


If readiness score is ready → queue A3 MatchingService
If readiness score is needs_info → queue C4 FollowUpService
Pure conditional logic, no LLM
C3: ProfileService


Manages client records
On new inquiry, matches by email or phone and pre-fills known fields
Pure CRUD operations
C4: FollowUpService


Triggers within 0 to 72 hours of a needs_info state
Rule-based scheduling, no LLM decision-making
Passes context to A5 CommunicationService for message sending
Does not send directly
C5: AnalyticsService


Runs SQL aggregations on lead and booking data
Caches results for dashboard display
No LLM involved

Workflows
W1: Inquiry intake Form submit → C3 profile check and pre-fill → A1 intake and structure → A2 readiness score → C2 routing → C1 sets lead state


W2: Location matching Lead state is ready → A3 runs semantic search → if good match: shortlist stored, C1 sets state to matched, A5 sends shortlist to client → if poor match: A3 sends one clarification to client via A5, client responds, A3 reruns → if still no match: C1 flags lead for ops team manual review


W3: Incomplete inquiry recovery State is needs_info → C4 triggers follow-up within 72 hours → A5 sends targeted message for missing fields only → client updates inquiry → A1 reprocesses → A2 reassesses → if ready: back to W2 → if no response after 7 days: C1 sets state to inactive → A6 picks up


W4: Booking and permit lifecycle Client confirms location → C1 sets state to booked → A4 generates permit checklist → A4 sets permit status to pending → ops team submits permits → A4 updates status to submitted → authority reviews → A4 updates status to in_review → if approved: A4 notifies C1, C1 advances to coordination stage, A5 notifies client → if rejected: A4 notifies ops and client via A5, flagged for manual resolution → shoot coordination begins → C1 sets state to closed on completion


C1 sends reminders via A5 if permit stays in any stage beyond expected duration
W5: Communication triggers Triggered by: any state transition by C1 → A5 sends state-change notification Also triggered by: time-based reminders (C1 detects overdue stages) → A5 sends reminder Also triggered by: inactivity detection (C1 detects no client action) → A5 sends nudge Also triggered by: permit status updates from A4 → A5 sends update to client and ops team


W6: Client profile reuse New inquiry → C3 matches existing profile → pre-fills form fields → client confirms → A1 processes confirmed data, skips re-collection of known fields


W7: Ops dashboard updates All state changes written by C1 → reflected in internal dashboard in real time, no separate sync job needed


W8: Issue resolution Complaint logged against lead or booking → assigned to ops owner → C1 tracks status → A5 sends acknowledgment to client


W9: Inactive lead nurturing No response after 7 or more days at needs_info or matched stage → C1 sets state to inactive → A6 picks up on weekly schedule → A5 sends re-engagement message → if client responds: state resets, back to W1 → if no response after extended period: C1 sets state to archived


System Principles
C1 WorkflowEngine is the backbone  nothing moves without it
Core Services own control, reliability, and all state transitions
AI Services assist where interpretation or personalization is needed
A5 CommunicationService is the only outgoing message layer
LLM never controls flow  it only assists decisions and crafts communication
More than half of this system is deterministic code
